english:
  title: Memorial Requesting the Rejection of the Northern Yuan Envoy
  author: Park Sang-chung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Majesty, I have served as a court official for many years now. It is an ancient principle that those in attendance at court may speak freely. There have been many matters of state worthy of discussion in recent times, yet I dared not speak. Was it because my office is not that of a remonstrator, and I feared to overstep my bounds? Or was it shame at seeking renown that sealed my lips? Now that the paths of speech lie open, with ministers and officials alike permitted to voice their counsel, it is surely because Your Majesty desires to hear strategies that benefit the people.

    Yet I humbly submit that while beneficial strategies abound, if the great foundation of our nation grows unstable, no benefit to the people can be secured. Our present condition resembles one who places fire beneath a stack of kindling and sleeps upon it, calling it safe because the flames have not yet risen. What thoughtful person could not grieve at this?

    The late King had scarcely passed away before his burial, yet Ming envoys remained within our borders. Who stirred up talk of serving the northern powers and bewildered our people? Who dared kill the envoys sent by the Dingliaowei? Who spread false rumors, causing soldiers loyal to the northern garrison to flee and desert? The late King commanded that the envoys be escorted—not by Kim Eui alone, but a high minister received this command and withdrew at Anju. Who was this? Who sought to deploy the northwestern army against the Dingliaowei? Why was Kim Eui's letter torn to pieces to silence him? Why were those who unlawfully took lives and the relatives of the rebel left unpunished? Why, after Kim Eui's rebellion more than a month ago, was this not reported to the court? Did Choe Won's embassy truly spring entirely from the intent of our high ministers?

    Now I hear that northern envoys return with those who rebelled alongside Kim Eui. When rebels return of their own accord, should we not question them, given their guilt? This reveals that Kim Eui's rebellion did not arise without cause—someone directed it. This is a moment of supreme danger, one that threatens our very survival.

    When matters stand thus, even the most foolish would perceive where advantage and justice lie. Yet those who speak now ignore these signs entirely—so great is their fear of calamity. By principle: to follow righteousness brings blessing; to follow transgression brings ruin. By circumstance: the South is strong, the North is weak—all know this truth. Yet to abandon loyalty and follow transgression is to commit the world's greatest injustice. To betray the strong and embrace the weak is folly in this present hour.

    As servants of the crown, we have betrayed the late King's policy of honoring the great power. Worse still, we have slain the envoy of the Son of Heaven and stolen his horses. What crime could be greater? Yet one or two corrupt ministers, harboring disloyalty and scheming to sell the nation for personal gain, would shift their guilt upon the state itself, determined to drag down our ancestral shrines and reduce our people to ruin. Is this not cause for deepest sorrow?

    When circumstances have reached such a pass, if Your Majesty does not act swiftly with two or three loyal and righteous ministers to discern and resolve this crisis, what shall become of our ancestral temples? What of our people?

    Yet I am no fool indifferent to life and death, nor a coward seeking safety. That I dare speak now, risking unknown punishment, springs from loyalty and righteous indignation that override all fear of harm. How then could I be moved by concerns of renown or by fear of overstepping?

    If Your Majesty will graciously weigh my words and take action, securing peace for our state and lasting welfare for our people, then should my humble body suffer ten thousand deaths, I would harbor not a single regret.
  footnotes:
    - 'Kim Eui (金義): A military figure who defected to the Jurchen north, an event that caused significant turmoil during this period of Korean history.'
    - 'Dingliaowei (定遼衛): A Ming military garrison that had jurisdiction over border regions.'
    - The 'fire beneath kindling' is a classical Chinese metaphor warning of hidden danger.
    - Park Sang-chung wrote this memorial during a time of intense political upheaval in Korea, when factions debated whether to maintain allegiance to Ming China or yield to pressure from the rising Jurchen powers.
